            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this Child Tax Credit calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                The Child Tax Credit (CTC) is a federal income tax credit that
                can significantly reduce your tax bill if you have qualifying
                children. This calculator gives you a quick estimate of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your maximum possible Child Tax Credit based on the number of
                  qualifying children.
                </li>
                <li>
                  How much of that credit is reduced (phased out) by your
                  income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  A rough split between the non‑refundable and potentially
                  refundable portions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  An estimate of the separate Credit for Other Dependents.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key assumptions (simplified current‑law model)</h3>
              <p>
                To keep the tool fast and easy to use, we model the CTC using
                common current‑law parameters:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Base Child Tax Credit per qualifying child under
                    17:</strong
                  >
                  $2,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Credit for Other Dependents:</strong> $500 per
                  eligible dependent (age 17+ or non‑child dependents).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Income phase‑out thresholds (MAGI):</strong>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Married filing jointly (MFJ):</strong> $400,000
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong
                        >Single / Head of Household / Married filing
                        separately:</strong
                      >
                      $200,000
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Phase‑out rate:</strong> 5% of income above the
                  threshold (i.e., $50 of credit lost for every $1,000 over the
                  threshold).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  1. Maximum credit before phase‑out
                </p>
                <p>
                  Let \( C \) be the number of qualifying children under 17 and
                  \( D \) the number of other dependents.
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Max CTC} = 2000 \times C \] \[ \text{Other dependent
                  credit} = 500 \times D \]
                </p>

                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">2. Income phase‑out</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( \text{AGI} \) be your adjusted gross income and \( T \)
                  the threshold for your filing status.
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Excess income} = \max(0,\ \text{AGI} - T) \] \[
                  \text{Phase‑out reduction} = 0.05 \times \text{Excess income}
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  The reduction cannot exceed your combined maximum credits: \[
                  \text{Phase‑out reduction} \le \text{Max CTC} + \text{Other
                  dependent credit} \]
                </p>

                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  3. Final estimated credits
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Total CTC after phase‑out} = \max\bigl(0,\ \text{Max
                  CTC} - \text{Phase‑out reduction on CTC}\bigr) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Other dependent credit after phase‑out} =
                  \max\bigl(0,\ \text{Other dependent credit} - \text{Phase‑out
                  reduction on ODC}\bigr) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Estimating refundable vs. non‑refundable portions</h3>
              <p>
                The actual rules for how much of the Child Tax Credit is
                refundable (the Additional Child Tax Credit) are complex and
                depend on earned income, number of children, and other factors.
                For planning purposes, we use a simple approach:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If you enter an estimated tax liability, we treat the CTC as
                  non‑refundable up to that amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Any remaining CTC is shown as “potentially refundable,” capped
                  at the total CTC.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you do not enter a tax liability, we assume roughly half of
                  your CTC could be non‑refundable and half potentially
                  refundable, but never more than the total.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is <strong>not</strong> an exact calculation of the
                Additional Child Tax Credit. Use it as a directional estimate
                only.
              </p>

              <h2>Who qualifies for the Child Tax Credit?</h2>
              <p>
                The IRS has detailed rules for who counts as a qualifying child.
                In general, all of the following must be true for each child you
                claim:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Age test:</strong> The child is under age 17 at the
                  end of the tax year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Relationship test:</strong> Your son, daughter,
                  stepchild, foster child, sibling, step‑sibling, or a
                  descendant of any of them (e.g., grandchild, niece, nephew).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Support test:</strong> The child did not provide more
                  than half of their own support during the year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Residency test:</strong> The child lived with you for
                  more than half of the year (with some exceptions for temporary
                  absences, birth, death, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dependent test:</strong> You claim the child as a
                  dependent on your tax return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Citizenship test:</strong> The child is a U.S.
                  citizen, U.S. national, or U.S. resident alien.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>SSN requirement:</strong> The child has a valid Social
                  Security Number issued by the Social Security Administration.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If a child does not meet all of these tests, they might still
                qualify you for the <em>Credit for Other Dependents</em> instead
                of the Child Tax Credit.
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding phase‑outs and planning strategies</h2>
              <p>
                Because the Child Tax Credit phases out at higher incomes, small
                changes in income can have a big impact on your final credit.
                The calculator helps you see how close you are to the threshold
                and how much credit you lose as income rises.
              </p>
              <h3>Common planning ideas (general information only)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Retirement contributions:</strong> Contributing to a
                  traditional 401(k) or IRA can reduce your AGI, potentially
                  preserving more of your CTC.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Timing of income:</strong> If you have control over
                  bonuses or self‑employment income, timing can affect which
                  side of the phase‑out threshold you fall on.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Filing status:</strong> In some situations, filing as
                  Head of Household instead of Single (if eligible) can change
                  your tax picture, though the CTC thresholds are similar.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are general concepts, not personalized advice. Always
                consult a qualified tax professional before making decisions.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool focuses on the <strong>federal</strong> Child Tax
                  Credit and Credit for Other Dependents only.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> model temporary COVID‑era
                  expansions (such as 2021 advance payments) or any future
                  legislative changes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not include state‑level child tax credits or other
                  family‑related credits (e.g., Earned Income Tax Credit, Child
                  and Dependent Care Credit).
                </li>
                <li>
                  It uses simplified formulas and assumptions and may not match
                  your actual IRS calculation.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For the most accurate results, use this calculator as a starting
                point, then review IRS publications (such as IRS Publication 972
                or its successors) and consider working with a tax professional
                or reputable tax software.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Child Tax Credit FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Who qualifies for the Child Tax Credit?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    A qualifying child must generally be under age 17 at the end
                    of the tax year, be your dependent, live with you for more
                    than half the year, not provide more than half of their own
                    support, be a U.S. citizen, national, or resident alien, and
                    have a valid SSN. You must also meet income limits and
                    filing requirements. The IRS has detailed rules and
                    exceptions in its official guidance.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is the Child Tax Credit refundable?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Part of the Child Tax Credit may be refundable as the
                    Additional Child Tax Credit. Whether and how much is
                    refundable depends on your earned income, number of
                    qualifying children, and tax liability. This calculator
                    provides a rough estimate of the refundable portion, but it
                    is not a substitute for the official IRS worksheets or
                    professional tax software.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How does income affect my Child Tax Credit?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Once your modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) exceeds the
                    threshold for your filing status, your Child Tax Credit and
                    Credit for Other Dependents are reduced by 5% of the amount
                    over the threshold. For example, if you are married filing
                    jointly with AGI $20,000 above the threshold, your combined
                    credits are reduced by about $1,000 (0.05 × $20,000).
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can both parents claim the same child?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. Only one taxpayer can claim a child as a qualifying
                    child for the Child Tax Credit in a given tax year. In
                    shared custody situations, parents may alternate years or
                    follow a court order. If both parents claim the same child,
                    the IRS applies tiebreaker rules. This calculator assumes
                    you are the only person claiming the child.
                  </p>
                </details>

                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does this calculator replace professional tax advice?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. This tool is for education and planning only. It
                    simplifies many rules and may not reflect your exact
                    situation. For official guidance, always refer to IRS
